          <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-6 poems">
            <h3>When Winter Kills</h3>
            <p>Black babes don’t grow on evergreen trees.
              They fall like autumn leaves;
              bodies brown, bodies gold,
              winter knocks the life from their throats.

              This chill is too familiar.
              Creeps up your spine,
              crawls through your veins,
              sits at the bottom of your stomach -
              the troll under the bridge,
              all shadow-hidden and legendary.

              And this cold isn’t kind to folk
              who are used to drinking sunlight
              for breakfast.

              So, remember to wrap your babe up warm.
              Tell him not to run along the sleet,
              before all he is, is a memory in ice.
            </p>
